body:
Did it happen all of a sudden?
Check your http certificates in the config folder, it looks like they got corrupt.

happened on the first start of v0.12-beta3 (was some self built v0.11.25 before).
How can I check them the certificates?

It's in syncthings home directory. Try to use openssl against it: 
http://support.qacafe.com/knowledge-base/how-do-i-display-the-contents-of-a-ssl-certificate/
Don't nuke it if it's invalid, and probably upload it somewhere.

`openssl rsa -in https-key.pem -text` and `openssl x509 -in https-cert.pem -text`
just display a lot of lines about the certificate/key, and no errors
And is the crash reproducible? If it is, then upload the certificates somewhere, as it's probably a bug in Go.

I can reproduce this on two devices but I think the error is somewhere else (after looking up how to read those panics :laughing:). Doesn't this

```
goroutine 232 [running]:
github.com/syncthing/syncthing/lib/scanner.func·004()
    /go/src/github.com/syncthing/syncthing/lib/scanner/walk.go:165 +0x3b0
created by github.com/syncthing/syncthing/lib/scanner.func·005
    /go/src/github.com/syncthing/syncthing/lib/scanner/walk.go:173 +0x3fc
```

say that the error is here: https://github.com/syncthing/syncthing/blob/master/lib/scanner/walk.go#L165
If `total` is zero we divide by zero here.

I wonder why you think it is the certificate (I want to learn something here^^), but I could upload them and generate new ones.
Ah yes, though interestingly the stack trace for TLS was at math/bin.divide ;)
